+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01CCfRBMPh5LMHAVC9EvuAn3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**Inversion Step 3 - Exploring the negation space:**\n\nWhat lives in the opposite? The key insight: **the common ancestor IS the snapshot at branch creation time**. Each branch stores its own document map (which starts as a deep clone of the parent). The merge algorithm should:\n\n1. At branch creation, record WHICH branch it forked from and snapshot the state at that moment\n2. On merge, retrieve that snapshot as the \"base\"\n3. Do a **field-level three-way diff**: for each key in base/ours/theirs, determine if it changed on one side, both sides, or neither\n4. Recurse into nested objects for deep structural merge\n5. Handle document-level operations (create/delete/unchanged) before field-level\n\nThe counterintuitive part: don't try to be clever with shared references — just snapshot cleanly at branch points and do honest structural comparison. Simplicity in the data model enables correctness in the merge."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":272,"cache_read_input_tokens":19501,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":272},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dac29a60-66bb-4c28-baf8-69f3d0048fd8","uuid":"011680bf-0634-4278-aa99-eadde5c04d96"}
